North Korea says 'no way' to disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that prolonged sanctions deepen mistrust in the United States and that there was no chance the country would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body’s annual general assembly that North Korea took “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling nuclear test facilities and committing to countering the proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see an appropriate response from the United States," he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can unilaterally disarm first."
While Ri echoed North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a nuclear disarmament approach “in stages,” according to which North Korea would be gradually rewarded for the steps taken, his statement seemed significant because he did not refuse unilateral, nuclear disarmament without discussion, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri alluded to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit of the current US president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work toward “nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula” while Trump gave a guarantee to North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States argues that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to give in to tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'nuclear disarmament first and foremost' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposes the 'declaration of an end to the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a vain dream of people who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the existing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other side in this nuclear disarmament problem was South Korea, instead of the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have ended in such a deadlock.”
Despite this, Ri’s tone was markedly different from last year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that directing North Korean missiles toward the U.S. mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Wicked President” Trump called Kim a “rocketist” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened the “total destruction” of North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament steps, but said much remained to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea’s nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a timeline for that, saying, “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months — it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
