New information about the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions of uneven algal blooms have been observed in the area of the districts of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, a consequence of the flowering of red algae, extends about 130 miles along the coast from the district of northern Pinelas to the district of southern Li.
Parts of the red tide can be seen as far as 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but the number is still smaller compared to last week.
Red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, the following concentrations have been observed: average concentrations in or on the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of Sarasota County, common to average concentrations in Charlotte County, common to high concentrations in or near Libre County.
In Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwest Florida over the past week.
